</p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#383838><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub42.ezboard.com/ucreeklass.showPublicProfile?language=EN>creeklass</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Boardfellow</span><br> <font color=#ff0000>(4/1/02 9:08:07 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub42.ezboard.com/fayonaerofrm6.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1140.topic&index=91>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Does illegality reduce demand?</span><hr size=1> I answer to some questions about my opinions earlier.  <br>
 I believe fully that making something illegal moves it to a different realm than it occupies when it is legal.  Some people (I'm not one of them) respect laws and are much less likely to do something if it is against the law.  A quote that I use in some training on drug use in the workplace is&lt;i&gt; &quot;What you permit, you condone.&quot; &lt;/i&gt;and I think that statement is very true.   Yes, I would have obtained drugs no matter what, just as I found a way to drink alcohol when I wasn't old enough legally, BUT I had lots of friends who didn't drink until they were legal and didn't use drugs because of the illegality of them.  In my opinion, keeping illegal drugs that way does indeed reduce the demand.  I don't have statistics, but I would imagine that a larger percentage of the population drank alcohol AFTER it became legal again than imbibed during prohibition.  <br>
<br>
One very effective deterrent to illegal drug use that I've seen is workplace drug testing.  I'm not arguing the right or wrong of testing, but I do know that it keeps people from using drugs if they want to keep their jobs.  For normal people (not addicts) drug/alcohol use is a rewards vs consequences decision.  Threat of job loss and/or breaking the law keeps many people away from drug use.  If the drugs became legal that would change.  Addicts, by the way, have this handy little tool called denial that helps them ignore the risks and consequences of drug and alcohol use.  Addicts (including alcoholics) will find a way to get high no matter what.<br>
<br>
Wayfarer, I'm really sorry I seemed to have made you angry.  I wasn't speaking about YOUR experience at all.  My statements were solely about the life I've lived and the lessons I've learned.  I didn't intend to belittle your opinion, nor make snide comments.  Nor was I talking about formal education when I said that experience and education changed my outlook on life.  I was talking about the education that we recieve from living life and learning (or not learning) the lessons presented there.  As a matter of fact, it sounds rather as if you and I have experienced many of the same events, but from different sides of the fence (police vs drug users).  <br>
<br>
One thing I pride myself on is my willingness to learn and to listen to other people, and to let their input change my opinion.  I do, however, as you have seen, value personal experiences much more than formal education.  I'd really be interested to know about studies that truly do adhere to scientific method.  Perhaps I was wrong in assuming they don't exist.<br>
<br>
My 'mysterious' education and experience that I spoke of that changed my mind about the legality of drugs was simply living through becoming addicted, getting into recovery and helping others try to kick drugs, and the view of drug use from here.  Trust me, the scenery is very different than it was when I was a beginner first taking my first hit off a joint.  As a result of my experiences, I now put on training sessions for employers about the nature of addiction and drug/alcohol use and abuse and how to deal with it in employees.  I've recieved quite a bit of formal training in the course of developing and presenting the course, and that has also broadened my view.  <br>
